		<img width="2500" height="1201" src="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-desert-mangroves.jpg" class="singlepostthumb wp-post-image" alt="David Borbón walking amongst 2-year old mangroves" decoding="async" fetchpriority="high" srcset="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-desert-mangroves.jpg 2500w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-desert-mangroves-520x250.jpg 520w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-desert-mangroves-768x369.jpg 768w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-desert-mangroves-1200x576.jpg 1200w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-desert-mangroves-1536x738.jpg 1536w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-desert-mangroves-2048x984.jpg 2048w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-desert-mangroves-900x432.jpg 900w" sizes="(max-width: 2500px) 100vw, 2500px" /><div class="post-thumbnail-caption">Baja California Sur, Mexico, has the most northern mangroves in the entire eastern Pacific. The trees are smaller than their tropical counterparts, but they’re ecological powerhouses as habitat and carbon sinks. Photo by Gemina Garland-Lewis </div>
			<article class="main container col4">
								<header class="maincol">
										<h1 class="pagetitle">The Mangrove Grandparents of El Delgadito</h1>
										<h2 class="dek singlepagecontainer">For over a decade, Ana María and David have led their community to restore Mexico’s desert mangroves with dedication, experimentation, and plenty of heart.</h2>
										<section class="singlebyline singlepagecontainer">
						<h3 class="invis">Authored by</h3>
						Text and photos by  
										<a href="https://hakaimagazine.com/profiles/gemina-garland-lewis/" class="tagmanager" id="author_link_top" >Gemina Garland-Lewis</a>								<br/>
												</section>
					 
					<aside class="singlebydatewords singlepagecontainer">
